-- Foreign Investors Buy Net 3.17 Billion Rupees of Indian Stocks
-- B y   P a r e s h   J a t a k i a
-- 2012-08-10T10:47:46Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-08-10/foreign-investors-buy-net-3-17-billion-rupees-of-indian-stocks.html
Overseas  funds  bought a net  3.2
billion rupees  ($57.5 million) of Indian stocks yesterday,
raising total investment in equities this year to 570.6 billion
rupees, according to the nation’s market regulator.  Foreigners bought 22.3 billion rupees of shares and sold
19.1 billion rupees, the Securities & Exchange Board of  India 
said on its  website  today. They invested 102.7 billion rupees in
stocks last month.  Foreign funds bought a net 574 million rupees of bonds,
taking total flows into debt this year to 241.1 billion rupees,
the data  show .  India’s $1.1 trillion stock market,  Asia ’s fifth-biggest,
is influenced by flows from overseas. Flows surged to a record
in 2010, making the  BSE India Sensitive Index (SENSEX)  the top performer
among the world’s top 10 markets. The largest-ever outflow in
2008 led the biggest annual slump of 52 percent.  Foreigners have invested 5.015 trillion rupees in stocks
and 1.448 trillion rupees in bonds since they were allowed into
the country in 1993.  The regulator provides data on shares bought and sold by
large investors, including trades in the primary and secondary
markets, with a delay of at least a day.  To contact the reporter on this story:
